79
00:10:36,300 --> 00:10:40,050
Have you ever had any heart
or asthma problems in the past?

80
00:10:40,180 --> 00:10:44,350
- No.
- Kidney or renal problems?

81
00:10:44,430 --> 00:10:46,890
- No.
- Any allergies?

82
00:10:49,310 --> 00:10:51,270
No.

83
00:10:56,110 --> 00:10:58,070
Where were you sitting
on the train?

84
00:11:02,120 --> 00:11:04,950
- Against the window.
- In the passenger car?

85
00:11:07,200 --> 00:11:09,170
Yeah.

86
00:11:11,420 --> 00:11:15,170
- Where are the other passengers?
- Was your family travelling with you?

87
00:11:17,840 --> 00:11:19,720
No.

88
00:11:19,840 --> 00:11:22,550
Did you get up from your seat?

89
00:11:28,180 --> 00:11:31,190
Are you certain
you were in the passenger car?

90
00:11:36,480 --> 00:11:38,440
Yes.

91
00:11:46,040 --> 00:11:48,870
Why are you looking at me like that?

92
00:11:48,950 --> 00:11:51,000
Your train derailed.

93
00:11:51,080 --> 00:11:53,830
Some kind of malfunction.

94
00:11:53,920 --> 00:11:56,880
They only found
two people alive so far--

95
00:11:56,960 --> 00:11:58,920
you and this man.

96
00:12:01,340 --> 00:12:04,680
His skull was cracked open and
most of his left side was crushed.

97
00:12:06,850 --> 00:12:08,970
And to answer your question,
there are two reasons...

98
00:12:09,060 --> 00:12:12,060
why I'm looking at you like this.

99
00:12:12,190 --> 00:12:14,980
One, because it seems
in a few minutes...

100
00:12:15,060 --> 00:12:19,360
that you will officially be
the only survivor of this train wreck.

101
00:12:19,440 --> 00:12:22,360
And two...

102
00:12:22,450 --> 00:12:24,410
because you didn't break one bone.

103
00:12:25,870 --> 00:12:27,830
You don't have a scratch on you.

104
00:14:13,930 --> 00:14:15,890
David?

105
00:14:18,560 --> 00:14:22,480
What happened in New York?

106
00:14:24,320 --> 00:14:26,700
I don't think I got the job.

107
00:14:28,530 --> 00:14:31,700
I'm still going to, uh--

108
00:14:31,780 --> 00:14:34,540
I'm still moving there.

109
00:14:34,620 --> 00:14:36,580
Just--

110
00:14:37,750 --> 00:14:39,710
Uh, just - just not now.

111
00:14:44,760 --> 00:14:46,880
Good night.

112
00:14:50,050 --> 00:14:52,010
Good night.

113
00:15:04,030 --> 00:15:06,070
Sara Elaston...

114
00:15:06,150 --> 00:15:09,320
social worker at
Broad and Locust Community Centre.

115
00:15:10,570 --> 00:15:12,700
We pray foryour soul.

116
00:15:14,910 --> 00:15:18,000
Kevin Elliot, businessman...

117
00:15:18,120 --> 00:15:21,000
father of six.

118
00:15:21,080 --> 00:15:23,040
We pray for your soul.

119
00:15:24,670 --> 00:15:26,800
Glen Stevens...

120
00:15:26,920 --> 00:15:30,180
researcher in the area
of leukemia...

121
00:15:30,300 --> 00:15:32,260
at Drexel University.

122
00:15:34,100 --> 00:15:36,060
We pray for your soul.

123
00:15:37,890 --> 00:15:40,020
Jennifer Pennyman...

124
00:15:40,140 --> 00:15:44,320
third-grade teacher
at Jefferson Elementary.

125
00:15:46,530 --> 00:15:48,490
We pray for your soul.

126
00:16:55,590 --> 00:16:58,760
- Yes?
- Is Noel in, ma'am?

127
00:16:58,850 --> 00:17:00,810
No, sir, he is not.

128
00:17:02,270 --> 00:17:05,100
I read about you in the paper.

129
00:17:05,190 --> 00:17:08,440
- What?
- I was in an accident once too.

130
00:17:08,520 --> 00:17:11,530
A horse almost trampled me to death.

131
00:17:11,610 --> 00:17:13,570
- Wow.
- Had him put down.

132
00:17:16,280 --> 00:17:18,240
That's a sad story.

133
00:17:21,160 --> 00:17:26,040
Could-- Could you ask Noel
something for me, please?

134
00:17:26,170 --> 00:17:28,290
Proceed.

135
00:17:28,420 --> 00:17:30,460
Would you ask him to check
how many sick days I've taken...

136
00:17:30,550 --> 00:17:32,670
since I've worked here?

137
00:17:32,760 --> 00:17:35,630
- That the entire message?
- Yes, ma'am.

138
00:17:39,560 --> 00:17:41,520
Thankyou.

139
00:18:19,800 --> 00:18:21,600
Hey, Noel.

140
00:18:21,680 --> 00:18:23,890
What, you hit your head on that train?

141
00:18:24,020 --> 00:18:25,980
Get your brain
to start working again?

142
00:18:27,560 --> 00:18:30,270
- What?
- Forty dollars.

143
00:18:31,900 --> 00:18:34,610
- Forty dollars what?
- You're gettin' a $40-a-week raise.

144
00:18:34,690 --> 00:18:36,650
That's it.

145
00:18:37,820 --> 00:18:40,990
I checked. You were right.
You've never taken a sick day.

146
00:18:41,120 --> 00:18:44,790
Five years, no sick day.
I get it. You want a raise.

147
00:18:44,910 --> 00:18:46,870
Smart way to make your point.

148
00:19:13,610 --> 00:19:16,150
- Is Joseph okay?
- Yeah.

149
00:19:16,280 --> 00:19:18,820
- He's asleep.
- Oh.

150
00:19:22,830 --> 00:19:25,910
I wanted to ask you a question.

151
00:19:26,040 --> 00:19:28,250
It's gonna sound a little strange,
but, uh...

152
00:19:28,330 --> 00:19:31,290
just think about it
for a second, okay?

153
00:19:31,380 --> 00:19:34,090
Okay.

154
00:19:34,170 --> 00:19:36,300
When's the last time I was sick?

155
00:19:36,420 --> 00:19:38,380
Do you remember?

156
00:19:41,970 --> 00:19:43,930
Um, I-I don't know.

157
00:19:46,020 --> 00:19:48,850
It's been a while.

158
00:19:48,930 --> 00:19:52,690
I haven't been sick this year,
I know that.

159
00:19:52,810 --> 00:19:54,940
Okay.

160
00:19:55,020 --> 00:19:56,980
Do you remember me gettin' sick?

161
00:20:00,200 --> 00:20:02,490
Um...

162
00:20:02,570 --> 00:20:04,870
not a specific day.

163
00:20:04,950 --> 00:20:07,160
And what's-what's this about?

164
00:20:09,460 --> 00:20:12,960
Audrey, do you remember me
ever getting sick?

165
00:20:13,080 --> 00:20:15,960
In the three years
we lived in this house?

166
00:20:16,050 --> 00:20:18,090
In the old apartment?

167
00:20:18,210 --> 00:20:21,180
Before Joseph was born?
Before we ever got married?

168
00:20:25,510 --> 00:20:27,470
I-I can't remember.

169
00:20:29,390 --> 00:20:31,690
Don't you think
that's kind of weird...

170
00:20:31,810 --> 00:20:35,980
not remembering one cold
or a-a fever or a sore throat?

171
00:20:38,280 --> 00:20:40,240
What do you think it means?

172
00:20:45,030 --> 00:20:47,950
Um...

173
00:20:48,040 --> 00:20:51,870
I think it means
I'm probably too tired to remember.

174
00:21:33,330 --> 00:21:37,710
No more sittin' in this room.
I let it go on long enough.

175
00:21:37,790 --> 00:21:40,960
I'm not goin' out there any more.
I'm not getting hurt again.

176
00:21:41,050 --> 00:21:45,340
- This was the last time, I told you.
- You can't do anything about that.

177
00:21:45,470 --> 00:21:47,760
You might fall between
this chair and that television.

178
00:21:47,890 --> 00:21:50,890
If that's what God has planned for you,
that's what's gonna happen.

179
00:21:50,970 --> 00:21:53,350
You can't hide from it
sittin' in a room.

180
00:21:57,440 --> 00:22:01,280
They call me Mr Glass at school
because I break like glass.

181
00:22:06,410 --> 00:22:08,370
You make this decision now...

182
00:22:09,830 --> 00:22:11,790
to be afraid...

183
00:22:13,450 --> 00:22:15,580
and you will never turn back.

184
00:22:17,330 --> 00:22:22,130
Your whole life,
you will always be afraid.

185
00:22:36,980 --> 00:22:39,520
- I got a present for you.
- Why?

186
00:22:41,230 --> 00:22:43,190
Forget why.

187
00:22:45,820 --> 00:22:47,780
You want it or not?

188
00:22:50,780 --> 00:22:52,990
Well, go get it, then.

189
00:22:53,080 --> 00:22:56,040
Where is it?

190
00:22:56,120 --> 00:22:58,750
On a bench...

191
00:22:58,830 --> 00:23:00,790
across the street.

192
00:23:14,890 --> 00:23:16,850
Someone's gonna take it.

193
00:23:18,890 --> 00:23:21,650
Then you better get out there soon.

194
00:24:36,100 --> 00:24:38,060
I bought a whole bunch.

195
00:24:42,600 --> 00:24:44,650
There'll be one of these
waitin' for you...

196
00:24:44,770 --> 00:24:46,900
every time you want
to come out here.

197
00:24:53,660 --> 00:24:56,740
They say this one
has a surprise ending.

198
00:25:05,670 --> 00:25:08,670
This is from Fritz Campion's
own library.

199
00:25:08,800 --> 00:25:13,680
This is before the first issue of
the comic book hit the stands in 1968.

200
00:25:13,800 --> 00:25:17,850
It's a classic depiction
of good versus evil.

201
00:25:17,930 --> 00:25:21,930
Notice the square jaw of Slayer,
common in most comic heroes.

202
00:25:22,020 --> 00:25:25,770
And the slightly disproportionate size
of Jaguaro's head to his body.

203
00:25:25,860 --> 00:25:29,940
This again is common,
but only in villains.

204
00:25:30,030 --> 00:25:32,400
The thing to notice about this piece...

205
00:25:32,530 --> 00:25:36,530
the thing that makes it
very, very special...

206
00:25:36,620 --> 00:25:39,700
is its realistic depiction
of its figures.

207
00:25:39,790 --> 00:25:41,830
When the characters
reached the magazine...

208
00:25:41,910 --> 00:25:43,960
they were exaggerated...

209
00:25:44,080 --> 00:25:46,290
as always happens.

210
00:25:46,420 --> 00:25:50,170
This is vintage.

211
00:25:53,050 --> 00:25:55,010
Well...

212
00:26:00,140 --> 00:26:02,600
wrap it up.

213
00:26:02,730 --> 00:26:05,100
You've made a considerably
wise decision.

214
00:26:10,570 --> 00:26:12,530
Well, my kid's gonna go berserk.

215
00:26:16,110 --> 00:26:18,160
Once again, please?

216
00:26:18,240 --> 00:26:21,040
My son Jeb--
it's a gift for him.

217
00:26:21,120 --> 00:26:24,000
- How old is Jeb?
- He's four.

218
00:26:27,000 --> 00:26:29,040
No.

219
00:26:29,170 --> 00:26:32,920
No, no, no, no, no.

220
00:26:34,420 --> 00:26:36,800
You need to go. Now.

221
00:26:38,590 --> 00:26:40,720
What'd - What'd I say?

222
00:26:40,810 --> 00:26:44,140
Do you see any Teletubbies in here?

223
00:26:44,230 --> 00:26:46,270
Do you see a slender plastic tag
clipped to my shirt...

224
00:26:46,350 --> 00:26:48,480
with my name printed on it?

225
00:26:48,600 --> 00:26:51,520
Did you see a little Asian child with
a blank expression sitting outside...

226
00:26:51,610 --> 00:26:55,360
in a mechanical helicopter that shakes
when you put quarters in it?

227
00:26:55,440 --> 00:26:59,030
No? Well, that's what
you see at a toy store...

228
00:26:59,160 --> 00:27:01,120
and you must think
you're in a toy store because...

229
00:27:01,240 --> 00:27:04,750
you're here shopping
for an infant named Jeb.

230
00:27:04,870 --> 00:27:07,870
Now, one of us
has made a gross error...

231
00:27:07,960 --> 00:27:11,130
and wasted the other person's
valuable time.

232
00:27:11,250 --> 00:27:13,380
This is an art gallery,
my friend...

233
00:27:13,460 --> 00:27:17,220
and this is a piece ofart.

234
00:27:32,570 --> 00:27:34,530
We're by appointment only.

235
00:27:36,320 --> 00:27:38,950
- I got a card from this store.
- Congratulations.

236
00:27:39,030 --> 00:27:42,620
You have a mailbox.
The exhibition isn't for two weeks.

237
00:27:42,740 --> 00:27:45,580
This one was under
the windshield wiper of my car.

238
00:27:48,460 --> 00:27:51,540
How certain are you that
you've never taken ill?

239
00:27:51,630 --> 00:27:54,170
Seventy-five percent.

240
00:27:54,250 --> 00:27:57,670
Well, that's not
certain at all, is it?

241
00:27:59,130 --> 00:28:02,050
That's hole number one.

242
00:28:02,140 --> 00:28:05,310
I'm going to be extremely skeptical
about all this.

243
00:28:05,430 --> 00:28:07,390
About all what?

244
00:28:08,930 --> 00:28:12,100
I'm assuming you've never been injured.
Would I be wrong in that assumption?

245
00:28:12,230 --> 00:28:14,190
Dad's been injured.

246
00:28:15,520 --> 00:28:18,530
Is the child correct?

247
00:28:18,610 --> 00:28:22,740
Yes, sir. In college,
I was in a car accident.

248
00:28:22,820 --> 00:28:27,700
- Was it serious?
- He couldn't play football any more.

249
00:28:27,790 --> 00:28:29,750
That's hole number two.

250
00:28:31,580 --> 00:28:33,540
That's a big one.

251
00:28:37,170 --> 00:28:41,090
Mr Price, can we talk about
the note that you left on my car?

252
00:28:41,220 --> 00:28:44,470
I've studied the form
of comics intimately.

253
00:28:44,550 --> 00:28:46,600
I've spent a third of my life
in a hospital bed...

254
00:28:46,680 --> 00:28:49,850
with nothing else to do but read.

255
00:28:49,930 --> 00:28:51,890
I believe comics
are our last link...

256
00:28:52,020 --> 00:28:55,690
to an ancient way
of passing on history.

257
00:28:55,820 --> 00:28:57,940
The Egyptians drew on walls.

258
00:28:58,070 --> 00:29:02,320
Countries all over the world still pass
on knowledge through pictorial forms.

259
00:29:02,410 --> 00:29:04,530
I believe comics
